@startuml pchat_epoch_fork_resolution
!theme plain
title Persistent Chat - Epoch Fork Resolution (POST_JOIN)

actor "New Member\n(Alice)" as alice
actor "Member B\n(Bob)" as bob
actor "Member C\n(Carol)" as carol
participant "Server\nCompanion" as server

note over alice, carol
  Scenario: Alice joins a POST_JOIN channel.
  Both Bob and Carol respond simultaneously,
  each generating a different epoch key.
  Fork must be resolved deterministically.
end note

== Trigger: Alice Joins Channel ==

alice -> server : fancy-pchat-key-announce
server -> bob : fancy-pchat-key-request\n{ requester: alice, relay_cap: 3 }
server -> carol : fancy-pchat-key-request\n(same request_id)

== Competing Responses (Fork Window) ==

bob -> bob : Generate epoch_key_B\nepoch_fp_B = SHA-256(key_B)[0..8]
carol -> carol : Generate epoch_key_C\nepoch_fp_C = SHA-256(key_C)[0..8]

bob -> server : fancy-pchat-key-exchange\n{ epoch_key_B, sender_hash: bob,\n  recipient: alice, request_id }
carol -> server : fancy-pchat-key-exchange\n{ epoch_key_C, sender_hash: carol,\n  recipient: alice, request_id }

server -> alice : Forward both responses\n(relay_cap = 3 allows multiple)

== Epoch Broadcasts to Existing Members ==

bob -> server : fancy-pchat-key-exchange\n{ epoch_key_B, recipient: carol,\n  request_id: null }
carol -> server : fancy-pchat-key-exchange\n{ epoch_key_C, recipient: bob,\n  request_id: null }
server -> carol : Forward Bob's epoch broadcast
server -> bob : Forward Carol's epoch broadcast

== 2-Second Grace Period ==

note over alice, carol
  All clients buffer outbound messages
  for 2 seconds after roster change,
  allowing epoch broadcasts to converge.
end note

== Deterministic Tie-Breaker ==

note over alice
  Alice receives two candidates for
  (channel_id, epoch) with same
  parent_fingerprint.

  **Tie-breaker rule:**
  Accept the epoch key from the sender
  with the lexicographically smallest
  cert_hash (lowercase hex comparison).

  If bob.cert_hash < carol.cert_hash:
    Winner = epoch_key_B
  Else:
    Winner = epoch_key_C
end note

alice -> alice : Apply tie-breaker\nDiscard losing fork\nLog discarded key for audit

bob -> bob : Apply same tie-breaker\n(identical rule, same winner)

carol -> carol : Apply same tie-breaker\n(identical rule, same winner)

== Fork-Window Message Re-Send ==

note over carol #FFF3CD
  If Carol sent messages encrypted with
  the losing epoch key during the fork
  window, she MUST re-send them:

  1. Generate new message_id (UUID)
  2. Set replaces_id = original_message_id
  3. Encrypt with winning epoch key
  4. Send replacement via PluginDataTransmission

  Receivers search BOTH volatile and
  persistent stores for replaces_id match,
  overwrite if found, insert if not.
end note

carol -> server : fancy-pchat-msg\n{ new_message_id,\n  replaces_id: old_message_id,\n  epoch: winning_epoch,\n  epoch_fingerprint: winner_fp }

server -> alice : Forward replacement
server -> bob : Forward replacement

alice -> alice : replace_message(replaces_id)\nSearch volatile + persistent\nOverwrite stale copy

bob -> bob : replace_message(replaces_id)\nSearch volatile + persistent\nOverwrite stale copy

== Converged State ==

note over alice, carol #D4EDDA
  All three clients now use the
  same winning epoch key.
  No ghost duplicates remain.
end note

@enduml
